course_metadata.title: Construction economics for decarbonisation and circular economy

content_chunks.content: This course introduces students to key economic principles within the context of the Architecture, Engineering, and Construction (AEC) industry. With a focus on construction economics, it emphasizes the significance of understanding long-term macroeconomic trends affecting the built environment, such as population growth, financial impacts, sustainability, and the circular economy. Students will explore shifts in supply and demand from a business perspective and learn how circular economy principles are reshaping the industry. By the end of the course, students will be able to understand macroeconomic trends to make informed, strategic decisions that support sustainable growth and competitiveness in the AEC sector.

Construction economics for decarbonization, circular economy principles, and sustainable AEC industry analysis - this course delivers comprehensive skills in applying economic theories to Architecture, Engineering, and Construction (AEC) decision-making. Master macroeconomic concepts in construction, analyze key macroeconomic indicators affecting the built environment, and apply microeconomic principles for competitive market analysis. Learn supply and demand theory in construction markets, implement circular economy principles for sustainable building, and evaluate economic impacts on developers, owners, designers, contractors, and material suppliers. Develop strategic decision-making capabilities for sustainable construction economics, create decarbonization strategies for long-term growth, and analyze population growth and financial impacts on construction industry competitiveness.
